model1 = lm(Mobility~Population, data = dat)
plot(y = dat$Mobility, x = dat$Population, main = 'Population', xlab = 'Population', ylab = 'Mobility')
abline(model1)

model2 = lm(Mobility~Income, data = dat)
plot(y = dat$Mobility, x = dat$Income, main = 'Income', xlab = 'Income', ylab = 'Mobility')
abline(model2)

abline(model3)

abline(model4)

#       .
  1. Create a new variable, called HE, whose value is TRUE if there is a higher education institution in the community, is FALSE if not. Replace all NA values in variables Colleges, Tuition and Graduation with 0. [ HE . community () HE TRUE, FALSE . NA 0 . ]
dat['Colleges'][is.na(dat['Colleges'])] = 0
dat['Tuition'][is.na(dat['Tuition'])] = 0
dat['Graduation'][is.na(dat['Graduation'])] = 0

dat$HE[dat$Colleges > 0 & dat$Tuition > 0 & dat$Graduation > 0] = TRUE
dat$HE[!(dat$Colleges > 0 & dat$Tuition > 0 & dat$Graduation > 0)] = FALSE
  1. All things considered, again. Fit a linear regression model, incorporating your findings in problems 3 and 4. If you have removed, created, or modified variables, explain.              Migration_out + Foreign_born + Single_mothers + HE, data = dat)
